    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>The Polar Museum (Polarmuseet) is operated by UiT — The Arctic University of Norway and is housed in the former customs premises on the Tromsø waterfront at Søndre Tollbodgate 11. <strong>The primary building is a red warehouse constructed in 1830</strong>, making it one of the oldest preserved structures in the city. The museum has been open to the public since 18 June 1978. A second historic building, the former boathouse, sits adjacent and holds temporary exhibitions.</p>
    <p>Seven permanent exhibitions cover distinct chapters of Arctic history. <strong>Sealing and Arctic fox trapping</strong> are documented through tools, clothing, and life-sized dioramas of trapper huts and hunting conditions on Svalbard. Additional sections address overwintering expeditions, the cultural and economic history of Svalbard from the 17th century onward, and the broader history of Norwegian polar exploration. The museum holds substantial material relating to Roald Amundsen and Fridtjof Nansen, including equipment, personal items, and expedition documentation. The balloon expeditions over the polar regions are covered in a separate section.</p>
    <p>Guided tours are not offered at fixed times but can be arranged by email to <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="6919061a1d04081a1d0c1b29190605081b041c1a0c1c04470706">[email&#160;protected]</a>. <strong>An English-language guide booklet is available at the entrance</strong>, as some exhibit labels are in Norwegian only. The museum is partially accessible by wheelchair — the ground floor is reachable, but a staircase without elevator leads to the upper floor. Audio guides and braille descriptions are available for visitors with visual impairments. The museum shop stocks polar-history publications and merchandise. Opening hours are daily 10:00–18:00; the museum is closed on 1 May and 17 May.</p>
  </div>

